content:
Create a Custom Lightning Web Component for OmniScript

You can add custom HTML, JavaScript, and CSS to an OmniScript by creating a custom Lightning web component.

Before previewing an OmniScript that uses custom Lightning web components, you must activate the OmniScript. If the OmniScript isn’t active, custom Lightning web components don't render in the preview. If you deploy changes to a custom Lightning web component that’s present in an Active OmniScript, the OmniScript displays the changes.

Requirements

To make a custom Lightning web component compatible with OmniStudio Lightning web components, set two metadata tags:

runtimeNamespace: Add the namespace of your Industries package.
isExposed: Set this tag to true.

Custom Lightning web components built outside of the package can’t use any Salesforce Lightning web component that uses resources or affects the component at runtime.

To prevent JSON validation errors when passing data from Custom Lightning web components to OmniStudio Lightning web components, precede double quotes in the data with the backslash (\) escape character.

For more information on extending OmniStudio Lightning web components, see Extend OmniStudio Lightning Web Components.

Custom OmniScript Lightning Web Components

You can create a custom Lightning web component by reviewing these component types:

OmniScriptBaseMixin component: Enable a custom component to interact with an OmniScript.
Standalone component: A custom standalone component that can’t extend the OmniScriptBaseMixin component or an OmniScript element Lightning web component.

To add a custom Lightning web component to an OmniScript, see Add Custom Lightning Web Components to an OmniScript.
title: Creating Custom Lightning Web Components for OmniStudio
